	<div>
		<h3>Job Description</h3>
		<p>
			The NYC Department of Buildings is seeking a Web Developer for its Analytics Development team. This position will provide support to the Analytics Development program at the Department, building on existing efforts, assessing progress to date, and supporting a program responsible for delivering advanced analytics and data science solutions. It will be critical for the successful candidate to provide development support to efforts related to predictive analytics, GIS and spatial analysis, and application development.
		</p>
		<br>
		<b>Duties will include:</b>
		<ul>
			<li>Developing web-based applications with Javascript, HTML, CSS, D3 and other front-end technologies.</li>
			<li>Using a range of programming languages to develop customized analytics solutions for internal and public users.</li>
			<li>Integrating front-end UI with backend service APIs using SOAP, XML, JSON, REST, or CSV.</li>
			<li>Evaluating GIS capabilities and supporting GIS development and operations using open-source spatial tools.</li>
			<li>Serving as a technical resource for special projects and technology initiatives.</li>
			<li>Special projects as assigned by the Chief Analytics Officer.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>

	<div>
		<h3>Minimum Qualification Requirements</h3>
		<ol>
			<li>
				A baccalaureate degree from an accredited college including or supplemented by 24 semester credits in computer science or a related computer field and one year of satisfactory full-time computer software experience in computer systems development and analysis, applications programming, database administration, maintenance and support, systems programming, data communications, mainframe development, mobile development, web development and design; or
			</li>			
			<li>
				A four-year high school diploma or its educational equivalent and five years of satisfactory full-time computer software experience as described in "1" above; or
			</li>
			<li>
				Education and or/or experience equivalent to "1" or "2" above. College education may be substituted for up to two years of the required experience in "2" above on the basis that 60 semester credits from an accredited college is equated to one year of experience. In addition, 24 semester credits from an accredited college or graduate school in computer science or a related field, or a certificate of at least 625 hours in computer programming from an accredited technical school (post high school), may be substituted for one year of experience. However, all candidates must have at least a four-year high school diploma or its educational equivalent and at least one year of satisfactory full-time experience as described in "1" above.
			</li>
		</ol>
		
	</div>

	<div>
		<h3>Preferred Skills</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>A masterâ€™s degree in Computer Science, Statistics, Information Systems, or related field </li>
			<li>
				5+ years of progressive experience in front-end web development, data analytics, data science, or business intelligence
			</li>
			<li>
				Documented experience developing with Javascript, HTML, CSS, D3 and other front-end technologies
			</li>
			<li>
				Excellent analytical and problem solving with strong communications and interpersonal skills
			</li>
			<li>
				Expert knowledge of one or more of the following languages (R, Python, SQL, Java)
			</li>
			<li>
				Proven experience developing and deploying web services
			</li>
			<li>
				Strong data visualization skills
			</li>
			<li>
				Experience developing open source geospatial data solutions using Leaflet, PostGIS, MapboxGL, Carto, or QGIS
			</li>
			<li>Basic knowledge of ESRI ArcGIS Server and ArcGIS Online</li>
			<li>Extensive experience with database management systems, including SQL Server, Oracle, or PostgreSQL</li>
			<li>
				Knowledge and experience with API and ETL concepts and tools
			</li>
			<li>
				Candidate should be an active Github contributor
			</li>
			<li>
				Ability to support a diverse team of data analysts, programmers, business analysts in a dynamic work environment
			</li>
		</ul>
	</div>

